# Service boundary and data ownership

## Rule
Every collection / table / kind / bucket path has exactly one owning service per `ai-brain/ownership-matrix.md`. Any other service reads or writes it only through the owner's public API or a published event — never via direct DB client.

## Why
The hybrid AWS + GCP topology already translates traffic through API-key callbacks and queues. Direct cross-service DB access would hide that translation, break tenant isolation, and bypass validation.

## Constraints
- No cross-service DB connections. `admin-backend` does not read `rates.*`, `fb-rates-go` does not read admin-backend master tables at the DB layer (uses the `/lookup/*` API).
- Shared-data candidates are onboarded into the owner service's API, not granted secondary DB access.
- Cross-service reads via REST use the owner's `BaseProxy`-wrapped client in the calling service.
- A change that requires "just this one query" against another service's DB is the wrong shape — file an API request on the owner.

## Examples

### Good
> quote-ai-backend needs freight rates → calls `fb-rates-go /v1/search/*` through its proxy layer with JWT.

### Bad
> quote-ai-backend opens a direct Mongo connection to the shared `rates` DB to read `tariff_freight_rates`.

